'''Atsiapat''' ({{lang-el|Άτσιαπατ}}), also spelt '''atsapat''' (Άτσαπατ), is the first in a sequence of three [[Greece|Greek]] [[Greek dances|traditional men dances]] performed in the region of [[Pontus (region)|Pontus]],<ref name="Pontian">{{cite web | url=http://www.angelfire.com/folk/pontian_net/dance/dance.htm | title=Pontian Dance | work=(Glossary) | accessdate=January 4, 2012}}</ref> as well as by [[Pontic Greeks|refugees]] of Pontos. Atsapat is characterized by short steps and exaggerated movements that resemble stretching. This dance is followed directly by [[Serra (dance)|Serra]]. The final dance in the sequence is the [[Pyrrhichios (dance)|Pyrrhichios]].
Atsapat is the Greek pronunciation of the Pontic Turkish city of [[Akçaabat]].<ref>DanceLessons.net: [http://dancelessons.net/dancehistory/HistoryofHoronDance.html History of Horon Dance]</ref> The region is famous for the virtuosity of its Pyrrhichios dancers.
