{{Politics of Guinea-Bissau}}

The '''National Unity Party''' ({{lang-pt|Partido da Unidade Nacional}}, PUN) was a [[political party]] in [[Guinea-Bissau]].

==History==
The party was established by [[Idrissa Djaló]] on 26 July 2001.<ref name=PP>Bogdan Szajkowski (2005) ''Political Parties of the World'', p273</ref> In the [[Guinea-Bissau legislative election, 2004|2004 parliamentary elections]] the party received 1.46% of the vote and failed to win a seat.<ref name=PP/> In the [[Guinea-Bissau presidential election, 2005|2005 presidential election]] Djaló finished eighth with 0.8% of the vote.

The party boycotted the [[Guinea-Bissau legislative election, 2008|2008 parliamentary elections]], with Djaló claiming that "the ballot will not resolve any of the persistent great problems in the country".<ref name=HD>Peter Karibe Mendy (2013) ''Historical Dictionary of the Republic of Guinea-Bissau'', Scarecrow Press, p328</ref> It did not contest presidential elections in [[Guinea-Bissau presidential election, 2009|2009]] or [[Guinea-Bissau presidential election, 2012|2012]], but supported the [[2012 Guinea-Bissau coup d'état|2012 military coup]].<ref name=HD/>

