'''Remigio Guido Barbieri''', O.S.B. (1836–1910) was an [[Italian people|Italian]]-born [[Bishop (Catholic Church)|Roman Catholic bishop]] who served as the [[Vicar Apostolic]] of [[Roman Catholic Diocese of Gibraltar|Gibraltar]] from 1901 to 1910.<ref name=bbarg>{{Catholic-hierarchy|bishop|bbarg|Bishop Remigio Guido Barbieri, O.S.B.|27 May 2014}}</ref>

Born in [[Siena]] in the [[Grand Duchy of Tuscany]] on 7 September 1836, he [[Profession (religious)|professed]] as a member of the [[Order of Saint Benedict]] on 20 June 1857 and [[Holy Orders|ordained]] a [[Priesthood (Catholic Church)|priest]] of that order on 24 March 1861.<ref name=bbarg/> He was appointed the Vicar Apostolic of Gibraltar and [[Titular Bishop]] of Theodosiopolis by [[Pope Leo XIII]] on 29 July 1901.<ref name=bbarg/> His [[consecration]] to the [[Episcopal polity|Episcopate]] took place on 10 November 1901; the principal [[consecrator]] was [[Vincenzo Vannutelli]], [[Roman Catholic Suburbicarian Diocese of Palestrina|Cardinal-Bishop of Palestrina]], with Giustino Adami, [[Titular Archbishop]] of Caesarea Ponti, and [[Edmund Stonor]], Titular Archbishop of Trapezus, serving as co-consecrators.<ref name=bbarg/>

Bishop Barbieri died in office on 15 April 1910, aged 73.<ref name=bbarg/>

